izenship and employment at a slower rate than non-Mexicans? Does their migration to the U.S. adversely affect the working conditions of lower-skilled workers already residing there? And how rapid is the intergenerational mobility among Mexican immigrant families? This authoritative volume provides a historical context for Mexican immigration to the U.S. and reports new findings on an immigrant influx whose size and character will force us to rethink economic policy for decades to come. Mexican Immigration to the United States will be necessary reading for anyone concerned about social conditions and economic opportunities in both countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aForeign workers, MexicanzUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxEconomic conditionsvCongresses. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsvCongresses. 0aMexican AmericansxCultural assimilationvCongresses. 0aMexican AmericansxEconomic conditionsvCongresses. 0aMexican AmericansxEmploymentvCongresses. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial conditionsvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aimmigrant, usa, america, american, mexico, capitol hill, debate, controversy, controversial, latin, foreign, economy, economic, history, historical, exodus, citizenship, employment, international, citizens, jobs, skills, workers, workplace, finance, money, wealth, power, policy, alien, congresses, workforce, gender, assimilation, academic, scholarly, essay collection, anthology, entrepreneurship, ethnic, ethnicity, race, emigration.1 aBlau, Francine D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorjas, George J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorjas, George J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCard, David, econtributor.4ct